<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Pinus contorta </i>includes four subspecies that have very different ecologies (Lotan and Critchfield 1990). Cones of <i>P. contorta </i>ssp. <i>contorta </i>tend to open at maturity but remain attached to the branches. Trees grow to 15 m in height and live for 100 years. They begin producing cones within 10 years. Seed crops usually occur every other year. Seed falls within 60 m of source trees, and seed viability is as high as 80 percent. Plants are shade intolerant (Cope 1993b). <br/>
<br/>
Stands occur on the North Coast of California and north along the coastline to Alaska. They occur on the leeward sides of active sand, stabilized dunes, marshy sloughs, rocky headlands, and bluffs subject to fog drip, heavy wind, and salt spray. In California, stands are small and scattered (Barbour 2007, Pickart and Barbour 2007, Vogl et al. 1977). Stands typically have abundant growth of nonvascular plants on the ground and trees, including two rare maritime lichens, <i>Bryoria spiralifer </i>and <i>B. pseudocapillaris </i>(Glavich 2003). <br/>
<br/>
The populations of <i>P. contorta </i>in the Klamath Mountains of southwestern Oregon and northwestern California (Critchfield 1957, Peck 1961) are most confusing. Coastal trees of ssp. <i>contorta </i>have persistent cones that open on the tree. Montane trees of ssp. <i>murrayana </i>have deciduous cones that open at maturity. Trees that grow on ultramafics of the Josephine ophiolite in the western Siskiyou Mountains, only 10 km east of the coast, have cones that are persistent and closed at maturity. These trees share characters with ssp. <i>latifolia </i>of the Rocky Mountains. Critchfield (1957) referred to these populations as “the Del Norte race,” suggesting that they might be another subspecies. Biven (1986) and Oliphant (1992) found different populations to be morphological and chemically variable, sharing leaf characteristics with plants of the coast and Rocky Mountains. We await molecular studies, and we include these populations in this alliance for now. <br/>
<br/>
Some authors recognize another taxon as ssp. <i>bolanderi, </i>the Mendocino Sands shore pine, which is a CNPS list 1B.2 plant. However, other studies (Wheeler and Critchfield 1985, Aitken and Libby 1994) showed this to be less distinct from ssp. <i>contorta. </i>It is recognized as a variety within ssp. <i>contorta </i>as var. <i>bolanderi </i>by some, and as a synonym of <i>contorta </i>(Kral 1993). We currently accept <i>P. contorta </i>ssp. <i>bolanderi, </i>and stands with this pine occur with <i>Hesperocyparis pigmaea </i>and <i>Pinus muricata </i>alliances and in this alliance. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
