<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text"><i>Pinus contorta </i>ssp. <i>contorta </i>is sensitive to fire and probably killed by most fires. The foliage is moderately flammable. Presence of shade-tolerant firs and hemlocks and fire-sensitive species, such as shore pine, indicate that fire is rare in this area. Fire return intervals are likely from 150 to 350 years and may not be cyclic (Cope 1993b). Ecologists in California have included stands of this species in their discussions of the state’s closed pines (see Barbour 2007, Stuart and Stephens 2006, Vogl et al. 1977), even though this conifer lacks serotinous cones and assumedly some role of fire. Green (1999) studied stands with trees exceeding 100 years in age at the Lanphere Dunes Unit of Humboldt Bay National Wildlife Refuge, where trees lacked charred bark, fire scars, or charcoal. Wind appeared to be the agent of stand disturbance.</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
