    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Ab). Stands on ultramafics described by Duebendorfer (1987) and Whittaker (1960) have distinctive understories of sclerophyllous shrubs not found elsewhere in the state (see Table 10.6 in Sawyer 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa, Ae, Ah-i). Larger stands are scattered mainly on coastal dunes north of Point Arena, near Fort Bragg in Mendocino Co., west of Humboldt Bay in Humboldt Co., and in the Point Saint George area in Del Norte Co. Green (1999) presented age, structure, and species composition in terms of tree density, basal area for stands at Lanphere Dunes (Barbour 2007, Pickart and Barbour 2007). Stands occur as far south as Mendocino Co. in white sand pine barrens along the coast (<i>P. contorta</i> ssp. <i>bolanderi</i>).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Many fungal pathogens, especially red ring rot (<i>Phellinus pini</i>), attack this species. Wind is another important disturbance factor in stands. Some stands are self-replacing; others are not (Green 1999). </div>
</div>

    

    

